'''Laster Technologies''' is a technology company based near [[Paris]], [[France]] that develops [[augmented reality]] eyewear.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.laster.fr/|title = Laster Technologies|date = 2011|accessdate = April 7, 2015|website = Laster Technologies Homepage|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> The company was founded in January 2005 by a group of experts in optics and visual image processing at CNRS (Centre Nacional de la Recherche Scientifique). Laster Technologies' patented technology<ref>{{ cite patent | country = US | number = 8976084 | status = | title = Portable augmented-reality head-up display device | pubdate = August 12, 2010 | gdate = | fdate = | pridate = | invent1 = Hamdani, Rachid | invent2 = Liu, Zile | assign1 = | assign2 = | class = }}</ref> is advertised under the trademark EnhancedView.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.laster.fr/technologies/description/|title = EnhancedView Technology Description|date = 2011|accessdate = April 7, 2015|website = Laster Technologies|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>
Laster Technologies products include [[eyewear]] devices coupled with [[software]] enabling [[man-machine interface]] functions such as gestural recognition, [[digital image correlation]] and tracking, and [[speech recognition|voice recognition]]. Potential applications for these products include defense and security, industrial maintenance, medical data monitoring and imaging, navigation, and sports.
In September 2006, the company won a research grant for the development of a prototype demonstrator for augmented reality in French Museums. It worked on this project with four partners: INRIA, Cité des Sciences et de l'Industrie, the Pierre-and-Marie-Curie University and Naska films. In July 2009, the company presented the augmented reality experience "Observe the Earth in 3D" at the inauguration of the permanent exhibition Explora, "Objective : Earth" at the Cité des Sciences et de l'Industrie. A projected video of Earth globe was placed at the center of a semi-circular table. Visitors are placed around the table and wear Laster glasses which allows them to see the Earth globe and overlay of virtual satellites around the Earth.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}
