{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = The Ancient Engineers | title_orig = | translator = | image = Ancient engineers.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[L. Sprague de Camp]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = Robert Flynn | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Engineering]] | publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] | release_date = 1963 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = 408 pp | isbn = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Ancient Engineers''''' is a 1963 [[science book]] by [[L. Sprague de Camp]], one of his most popular works. It was first published by [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] and has been reprinted numerous times by other publishers. Translations into German and [[Polish language|Polish]] have also appeared. Portions of the work had previously appeared as articles in the magazines ''[[Fate Magazine|Fate]]'', ''[[Isis (journal)|Isis]]'' and ''[[Science Digest]]''.<ref name="Laughlin">{{cite book | last=Laughlin | first=Charlotte | author2=Daniel J. H. Levack | title=De Camp: An L. Sprague de Camp Bibliography | location=San Francisco | publisher=Underwood/Miller | year=1983 | pages=23–24}}</ref><ref name="ISFDb">{{isfdb title|id= 831602 |title=The Ancient Engineers}}</ref>
==Contents== The work is an examination of [[engineering]] through the ages from 3000 BC to 1519 AD, from the monumental works of [[Ancient Egyptian technology|the Egyptians]] through the speculative inventions of [[Leonardo da Vinci]]. The technological legacies of [[Mesopotamia]], Egypt, [[Greece]], [[Rome]], [[History of science and technology in China|China]], the [[Inventions in medieval Islam|medieval Arabs]] and Europeans, and [[Renaissance]] Europe, are all covered in separate sections, focusing particularly on [[Architectural engineering|architectural]], [[Military engineer|military]] and [[civil engineering]].
==Review== The following review is often quoted in reference to this book: "Mr. de Camp has the trick of being able to show technology engaging in feats as full of derring-do as those of Hannibal's army. History as it should be told." —[[Isaac Asimov]], ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'', 1963
